# Tokens

## Spacing Tokens

A semantic scale of spacing tokens for different typographic contexts and visual hierarchy.

| Token                     | Description                         | Default Value                |
| ------------------------- | ----------------------------------- | ---------------------------- |
| `--paragraph-spacing-sm`  | Small spacing for list items        | `var(--space-3)`             |
| `--paragraph-spacing-md`  | Standard paragraph and list spacing | `var(--space-4)`             |
| `--paragraph-spacing-lg`  | Large spacing for blocks and quotes | `var(--space-6)`             |
| `--paragraph-line-height` | Line height within paragraphs       | `var(--line-height-relaxed)` |

## Text Flow Tokens

Control text alignment, indentation, and hyphenation for different document styles.

| Token                     | Description                                   | Default Value |
| ------------------------- | --------------------------------------------- | ------------- |
| `--paragraph-text-align`  | Text alignment (left, right, center, justify) | `left`        |
| `--paragraph-text-indent` | First-line indentation                        | `0`           |
| `--paragraph-hyphens`     | Hyphenation control (none, auto, manual)      | `none`        |

## Typography Enhancement Tokens

Advanced typography features. A _lead_ paragraph is the first paragraph after a heading.

| Token                          | Description                                     | Default Value |
| ------------------------------ | ----------------------------------------------- | ------------- |
| `--paragraph-orphans`          | Minimum lines at bottom of page/column break    | `2`           |
| `--paragraph-widows`           | Minimum lines at top of page/column break       | `2`           |
| `--paragraph-text-wrap`        | Text wrapping algorithm (auto, pretty, balance) | `auto`        |
| `--paragraph-lead-font-size`   | Font size for lead paragraphs                   | `inherit`     |
| `--paragraph-lead-font-weight` | Font weight for lead paragraphs                 | `inherit`     |
| `--paragraph-lead-text-indent` | First-line indentation for lead paragraphs      | `0`           |

# Usage

## Spacing Context

Each spacing token serves a specific purpose in research and technical document layout:

**sm (0.75rem)**: Used for `li p+p` - multiple paragraphs within list items need tighter spacing.

**md (1rem)**: Standard spacing for regular content:

- `p` elements - body text paragraphs
- `ul, ol` - list containers

**lg (1.5rem)**: Larger spacing for special blocks that need visual separation:

- `pre` - code blocks and algorithms
- `blockquote` - quoted literature or equations
- `hr` - section dividers

## Text Flow Control

**Text alignment**: Choose between `left` (web standard), `justify` (scholarly papers), `center` (titles), or `right` (specialized layouts).

**Text indentation**: Use `--paragraph-text-indent` for traditional scholarly formatting. Common values:

- `0` - Web/modern style (no indent)
- `1.5em` - Standard scholarly indent
- `1.463rem` - Traditional LaTeX paragraph indent

**Hyphenation**: Control word breaking:

- `none` - No hyphenation (web default)
- `auto` - Automatic hyphenation (recommended for justified text)
- `manual` - Only break at explicit hyphens

## Typography Enhancement

**Orphans and widows**: Control how paragraphs break across pages/columns to prevent single lines appearing isolated.

**Text wrap**: Modern browsers support improved line breaking with `text-wrap: pretty` for better readability.

# Patterns

## Research Paper Style

Traditional scholarly document with justified text and paragraph indentation:

```css
:root {
  --paragraph-text-align: justify;
  --paragraph-text-indent: 1.5em;
  --paragraph-hyphens: auto;
  --paragraph-spacing-md: 1rem;
  --paragraph-spacing-lg: 1.5rem;
}
```

```html raw
<div
  style="
  --paragraph-text-align: justify;
  --paragraph-text-indent: 1.5em;
  --paragraph-hyphens: auto;
  --paragraph-spacing-md: 1rem;
  --paragraph-spacing-lg: 1.5rem;
  max-width: 60ch;
"
>
  <h3>Methods</h3>
  <p>
    We conducted a randomized controlled trial to evaluate the effectiveness of
    the proposed algorithm. Participants were recruited from three research
    institutions across North America between January 2023 and March 2024.
  </p>
  <p>
    The primary endpoint was computational efficiency measured in operations per
    second. Secondary endpoints included memory usage, error rates, and user
    satisfaction scores collected via standardized questionnaires.
  </p>
  <p>
    Statistical analysis was performed using R version 4.3.0. All tests were
    two-tailed with significance set at p &lt; 0.05. Missing data were handled
    using multiple imputation techniques.
  </p>
</div>
```

